IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Detailed Crash Investigation Supplement (For review by the MSPCrash Team) Section I. - Narrative On September 28, 2023, at approximately 0910 hours, Troopers from the Cumberland Barrack responded to I-68 eastbound west of Winchester Road for a two vehicle collision. V1: 2023 Mercedes van, Missouri registration EK1K9V D1: Hasan Makhmudov, 3/30/1985 V2: 2004 Peterbilt, Maryland registration 55X876, US DOT 1098714, Sloan Septic D2: Robert Lee Hardmand, 4/20/1959. It was initially believed that Makhmudov had sustained life-threatening injuries. After he was removed from his vehicle, he was flown by Trooper 5 to Conemaugh Memorial Hospital in Johnstown, Pennsylvania. It was determined that his injuries were not life-threatening. I was responded to the scene to assist in the investigation. V1 was against the guardrail in the median with severe frontal damage. V2 was stopped on the right shoulder further east with damage to the left rear corner. I digitally photographed the vehicles, marked the evidence and documented the scene with a sUAS. MSP Syscom Case Number: 23-04106 NOTAM: CLE 09/733 Aircraft:Crash Team UAS 9 FA34WNR733 Autel Evo II 6K HA9921441404 Flight Time: 8 minutes 183 digital photographs were taken Mapping was completed with a manual flight M/T Wagoner of the Finzel Weigh and Inspection Facility responded to conduct a post crash inspection of V2. Section II. - Attachments that were included in for this report: The following items were attached to this report: 183 sUAS digital photographs were uploaded to Veripic 94 ground based digital photographs were uploaded to Veripic Conclusion: Due to the upgraded condition of the driver of V1, this case will be handled on the ACRS by ST Bennett. This case is closed. Sgt. David Zanoni Crash Team - Cumberland Office 1125 National Highway Cumberland, MD 21502 301-729-6470

CRASH SUMMARY: margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:left">On September 28, 2023, at 0910 hours, the Cumberland Barrack received a call for a two vehicle collision involving a Commercial Motor Vehicle (CMV) eastbound I-68 near Winchester Road. Due to the involvement of a CMV, Cadet Brady Gray and I responded to the scene to assist with the investigation. Upon arrival I observed a white sprinter van (MO Registration: EK1K9V), driven by Hasan Makhmudov,(DOB: 03/30/1985, Union, NJ). The van was resting against the center median guardrail. base64," style="height:262px; margin:5px 10px; width:350px" /> The van had sustained heavy damage to the front and drivers side. Makhmudov was still in the vehicle and was extracted by EMS personal in an unconscious state. It should be noted that the drivers seat appeared to have been broken off its mount. An unsecured tool box appears to have impacted the rear of the drivers seat. base64," style="height:263px; margin:5px 10px; width:350px" />base64," style="height:263px; margin:5px 10px; width:350px" /> Just east of the vans position on the right shoulder was a Red Peterbuilt tanker truck. The truck(2004 Peterbuilt, MD Registration: 55X876) was owned by Sloans Septic and Pumping(US DOT#: 1098714) from Grantsville,MD. The vehicle driver was Robert Lee Hardman Jr, (DOB: 04/20/1959) from Barton, MD. base64," style="height:233px; margin:5px 10px; width:350px" />base64," style="height:233px; margin:5px 10px; width:350px" />base64," style="height:233px; margin:5px 10px; width:350px" /> The truck had sustained heavy damage to the left rear fender and the rear crash protected guard. The vehicle was still operational and the driver had refused treatment at the scene. Hardman seemed healthy and did not appear to be impaired by any substance or fatigued. The interstate was closed for Trooper 5 to air lift Makhmudov to Conemaugh Memorial Medical Center, Johnstown, MD. Sgt. Zanoni of the MD State Police Crash Team responded to process the scene. A preliminary investigation revealed that Makhmudov was observed by witnesses moving at a high rate of speed in lane one of eastbound I-68 near Winchester Road. Makhmudovs vehicle left lane one and struck the rear of the CMV traveling in lane two. Makhmudovs vehicle then struck the center median guardrail. Sgt Zanoi contacted me later by phone and stated that Mr. Makhmudov injuries were not life-threatening and he would not be reconstructing the collision. A North American Standard Level One inspection was conducted on the CMV in a nearby SHA Facility parking lot. No pre-collision violations were found during the inspection. S/T Shawn Bennett(Cumberland Barrack) was assigned the ACRS report. margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:center"> margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:left"> B. C. COMMERCIAL VEHICLE DETAILS Vehicle #1: Year: 2004 Make: Peterbilt Model: Four Axle Tanker VIN: 1NPALBOX44D826930 Registration: 55X876 State of Issuance: MD Weight and Measurements: Vehicle was not weighed because I did not have mobile scales at that time. The driver also did not want to return to scale facility because of the uncertainty of the vehicles condition. Brakes: The vehicle was driven to the SHA facility on Vocke Road, LaVale, MD. The brakes were inspected in the parking lot. The air system was operational and I was able to obtain the brake measurements. Cadet Brady Gray assisted me with the inspection. No brake violations were found during the inspection. margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:center"> margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:left">D. INSPECTION RESULTS: The inspection was conducted at MD SHA facility District Office 6 located at1251 Vocke Rd, La Vale, MD 21502. The location was less than two miles away from the crash scene. The vehicle was moved there for a more safe working environment. The SHA facility has a flat paved parking lot and free from public traffic. At that location I conducted a North American Standard Level One inspection. All of the vehicle critical systems were intact so no outside assistance was needed. Cadet Brady Gray assisted me with the inspection. No pre-collision violations were located during the inspection. The driver was polite and cooperative during the entire inspection. After the submission of the inspection and release of the driver from the scene, it was discovered that the driver did not possess an N endorsement. This was an oversight on my part during the inspection process. I have contacted the company owner Mysty Sloan, and she was unaware of this fact. Mrs. Sloan stated that she would be dealing with the driver and evaluating continued employment with the company. Due to these facts I will not be adding the violation to the inspection or charging the driver due to my own error at the time.
